I thought about a security vulnerability with email / gmail communications.

could someone forge an email, that looks like me send it to cosa, and start interacting with it?


Yes, that's a real attack vector and worth taking seriously. Email From: headers are trivially spoofable — anyone can send an email claiming to be from your address.

The Threat
Attacker → sends email "From: jj@gmail.com" → COSA inbox
COSA sees apparent JJ email → executes command
If COSA just checks the From: header, it's fooled.

Mitigations (layered)
1. Check Gmail's authentication metadata (SPF/DKIM) The Gmail API returns authentication results on each message. A legitimate email from your actual Gmail will pass DKIM; a spoofed one typically won't. COSA should reject anything that fails DKIM for your domain.

2. Thread-locking (simplest & most effective) Only process emails that are replies to threads COSA itself initiated. An attacker can't forge a valid Gmail thread ID. This alone cuts 95% of the attack surface.

3. Shared secret / passphrase Require a rotating keyword or PIN embedded in commands. Even if someone spoofs the From header and guesses the thread, they don't know the secret.

4. Whitelist by Message-ID chain Only trust messages where the In-Reply-To header matches a Message-ID that COSA generated and stored.

Recommended approach for COSA
Thread-locking + DKIM check is probably sufficient for your use case. The secret passphrase adds a nice extra layer without much friction for you.

The three layers work as independent gates — an attacker has to defeat all three simultaneously:
Layer 1 — Thread lock is the cheapest check. COSA only processes emails that reply to threads it started. An attacker can't forge a valid Gmail In-Reply-To header pointing to a Message-ID that COSA generated, because those IDs are server-assigned by Gmail. This alone stops untargeted attacks cold.
Layer 2 — DKIM catches a sophisticated attacker who somehow knows your email address and tries to spoof it via a different mail server. The Gmail API exposes authentication results on every message — check that dkim=pass domain=gmail.com is present. A spoofed email routed through another server will fail this.
Layer 3 — Rotating passphrase is your last line. Even if someone compromised your actual Gmail account (session hijack etc.), they'd still need the current token. The token advances every exchange, so a captured token is useless after one use — no replay attacks.
The silent drop on rejection is intentional — sending an error reply would confirm to an attacker that they're targeting the right inbox and that COSA is alive.
For the token rotation mechanism, the simplest approach is a TOTP-style scheme using a shared seed — both you and COSA derive the current 6-digit code from the same seed + timestamp, rotating every 5 minutes. No state synchronization needed.


The cleanest approach for your stack is standard TOTP — the same algorithm behind Google Authenticator. No external service, no state sync, just a shared secret and time.

Here's the full implementation for both sides.

COSA side — totp.js (Bun-native, no deps)
jsimport { createHmac } from "crypto"

const SECRET_B32 = process.env.COSA_TOTP_SECRET  // 32-char base32

// base32 decode (RFC 4648, no padding needed)
function b32decode(s) {
  const alpha = "ABCDEFGHIJKLMNOPQRSTUVWXYZ234567"
  let bits = 0, val = 0
  const out = []
  for (const c of s.toUpperCase().replace(/=+$/, "")) {
    val = (val << 5) | alpha.indexOf(c)
    bits += 5
    if (bits >= 8) { bits -= 8; out.push((val >> bits) & 0xff) }
  }
  return Buffer.from(out)
}

function totp(secret, window = 0, step = 300) {
  const counter = Math.floor(Date.now() / 1000 / step) + window
  const buf = Buffer.alloc(8)
  buf.writeBigInt64BE(BigInt(counter))
  const hmac = createHmac("sha1", b32decode(secret)).update(buf).digest()
  const offset = hmac[19] & 0xf
  const code = ((hmac.readUInt32BE(offset) & 0x7fffffff) % 1_000_000)
    .toString().padStart(6, "0")
  return code
}

// validate with ±1 window tolerance + nonce guard
const usedNonces = new Set()

export function validateToken(token) {
  for (const w of [-1, 0, 1]) {
    const expected = totp(SECRET_B32, w)
    if (token === expected && !usedNonces.has(token)) {
      usedNonces.add(token)
      setTimeout(() => usedNonces.delete(token), 15 * 60 * 1000)
      return true
    }
  }
  return false
}

export function currentToken() {
  return totp(SECRET_B32)
}
COSA email parser — email-auth.js
jsimport { validateToken } from "./totp.js"

// Command format: "cosa: <command> <token>"
// e.g.  "cosa: status 847291"
//       "cosa: restart baanbaan 847291"

const CMD_RE = /^cosa:\s+(.+?)\s+(\d{6})\s*$/im

export function parseCommand(emailBody) {
  const match = emailBody.match(CMD_RE)
  if (!match) return null

  const [, command, token] = match
  if (!validateToken(token)) return null   // wrong token or replay

  return command.trim()
}
