cosa: status 847291
COSA strips the token before logging the command. You never type the token manually — your authenticator app shows it, you glance at it, you append it.

What this buys you
The nonce log blocks replay within the 15-minute window. After that the window has rotated anyway, so a captured token is permanently useless. Combined with the thread-lock and DKIM checks from Layer 1 and 2, an attacker needs simultaneous access to your Gmail session, your TOTP seed, and a live COSA-originated thread — that's not a realistic attack surface for a restaurant POS agent.

Here's the complete COSA project — 9 modules + env template + setup script.
How the SAM + FSM decomposition works:
The FSM in cosa-fsm.js is purely declarative — 5 states, 8 transitions, enforceAllowedActions: true. It can't land in an illegal state and can't accept a rogue action out of sequence. The SAM instance in index.js merges three concerns:

emailLoopFSM.acceptors — handle the pc (program counter) transitions
Your application acceptors (in model.js) — handle the data mutations (pending email, command, dispatch result) completely separately from control flow
emailLoopFSM.stateMachine + nap as reactors — the FSM enforces transitions, the NAP drives the async chain

The NAP is the loop engine. After every SAM step, nap(state) fires synchronously, inspects state.pc, and launches the appropriate async work. When that work completes it fires the next FSM intent, which triggers another SAM step, which triggers the NAP again. The _inflight guard prevents double-firing during async work, and the FSM's own enforceAllowedActions is a second backstop.
